Introduction and Rationale:¶

Crowdfunding platforms are the lifeblood of ideas and projects that need a pedestal to get funds and grow. Kickstarter is one such platform that focuses on celebrating creative projects and raise a target amount to be pledged within a stipulated timeframe.

This project is directed at analyzing Kickstarter from two perspectives Internally, to understand campaign performance and externally, from a start-up creator's perspective, to understand whether Kickstarter would be the right choice for promoting their idea.

The dataset chosen contains Campaign level details including the final outcome - success or failure and is hosted publicly on Kaggle https://www.kaggle.com/kemical/kickstarter-projects?select=ks-projects-201801.csv.

Data cleaning and Preprocessing¶

The columns USD Pledged, Goal and Pledged will not be used for the analysis as there are alternate columns titled usd_pledged_real and usd_goal_real. These columns are made available in the original dataset through conversion from an external API for foreign exchange conversion.

In [13]:
# Creating a copy of the original dataset for cleaning
data_clean=data.copy()
In [14]:
#dropping unnecessary columns
data_clean.drop(columns=['usd pledged','goal','pledged'],axis=1,inplace=True)
In [15]:
#dropping 4 rows whose "name" value was NaN
data_clean.dropna(subset=['name'],inplace=True)
In [16]:
#removing those rows whose "country" value was 'N,0"'
mask=data_clean['country']!='N,0"'
data_clean=data_clean[mask]
In [17]:
#taking out those rows whose "state" value was either "successful" or "failed"
mask1=data_clean['state']=='successful'
mask2=data_clean['state']=='failed'
data_clean=data_clean[mask1 | mask2]
In [18]:
#removing those rows where backers=0 but usd_pledged_real>0
mask1=data_clean['backers']==0
mask2=data_clean['usd_pledged_real']>0
data_clean=data_clean[~(mask1 & mask2)]
In [19]:
#removing those rows where usd_pledged_real>=usd_goal_real but state=failed
mask1=data_clean['usd_pledged_real']>=data_clean['usd_goal_real']
mask2=data_clean['state']=='failed'
data_clean=data_clean[~(mask1 & mask2)]
In [20]:
#removing those rows where usd_pledged_real<usd_goal_real but state=successful
mask1=data_clean['usd_pledged_real']<data_clean['usd_goal_real']
mask2=data_clean['state']=='successful'
data_clean=data_clean[~(mask1 & mask2)]
In [21]:
#separating year from the 'launched' date
data_clean['year']=pd.to_datetime(data_clean['launched']).dt.year
In [22]:
#removing those row where year=1970 since it's an input error
mask=data_clean['year']!=1970
data_clean=data_clean[mask]
In [23]:
# Converting ID to object type
data_clean['ID']=data_clean['ID'].astype('object')

Feature Engineering¶

Creating additional variables useful for analysis.

In [26]:
#calculating duration of the project on kickstarter website
data_clean['launched']=pd.to_datetime(data_clean['launched']).dt.date
data_clean['deadline']=pd.to_datetime(data_clean['deadline']).dt.date
data_clean['duration']=data_clean['deadline']-data_clean['launched']
data_clean['duration']=data_clean['duration'].dt.days
In [27]:
#caluclating the difference between usd_goal_real and usd_pledged_real
data_clean['difference']=data_clean['usd_goal_real']-data_clean['usd_pledged_real']
In [28]:
# Dividing goal amount into categorical bins for ease of understanding
# Creating labels for goal amount bins
labels = ['Zero - 100', '100 - 1K', '1K - 5K','5K - 50K','50K - 100K','100K - 500K','500K - 1M','1M - 5M','5M+']

bins=[0,100,1000,5000,50000,100000,500000,1000000,5000000,20000000] # the lower bin value is included in pd.cut
data_clean['project_scale']=pd.cut(data_clean['usd_goal_real'],bins=bins,labels=labels)
In [29]:
# Creating binary flag for succesful projects used for calculating success rate
data_clean['success']=np.where(data_clean['state']== 'successful', 1, 0)
In [30]:
#separating month from the 'launched' date
data_clean['month']=pd.to_datetime(data_clean['launched']).dt.month
In [31]:
# Converting month and year to object type
data_clean['month']=data_clean['month'].astype('object')
data_clean['year']=data_clean['year'].astype('object')

Predictive Analysis: Classification Model¶

Predicting probability of Project Suceess¶

As a value add to the end users, Kickstarter can utlize a classification model to predict the probability of success of the project, given a few key parameters like project cateogry, intended duration and required goal amount, based on historical data. A prototype of the same is developed below, using a Decision Tree classifier.

In [81]:
# for the model, we will use 'usd_goal_real','main_category','category' and 'country' as independent variables and 'state' as
# dependent varaiable
data_for_model=data_clean[['name','usd_goal_real','main_category','category','country','state']].copy()

We will dummy code all the categorical varaibles as Decision Tree model cannot take object variables as 'input'

UDFs for encoding required variables¶

In [82]:
# dummy coding top 3 most occuring countries in the dataset
def USA_dummy(x):
    ''' dummy code country "US" as 1 and other countries as 0.
        Here, x is the value from a single row of the column "country" '''
    if(x=='US'):
        return 1
    else:
        return 0
    
def UK_dummy(x):
    ''' dummy code country "GB" as 1 and other countries as 0.
        Here, x is the value from a single row of the column "country" '''
    if(x=='GB'):
        return 1
    else:
        return 0
    
def CA_dummy(x):
    ''' dummy code country "CA" as 1 and other countries as 0.
        Here, x is the value from a single row of the column "country" '''
    if(x=='CA'):
        return 1
    else:
        return 0
    
data_for_model['country_US']=data_for_model['country'].apply(USA_dummy)
data_for_model['country_GB']=data_for_model['country'].apply(UK_dummy)
data_for_model['country_CA']=data_for_model['country'].apply(CA_dummy)
